# RepSnap

A private gym social app for you and your friends — share workout and progress photos in a small, close-knit feed. Think Instagram, but just for the gym and just for your circle.

> **Status:** Frontend prototype. Auth and data are faked with `localStorage`, so everything runs in the browser with no backend. Not built for real/shared use yet.

## Features

- **Accounts** — sign up and log in (stored locally on your device)
- **Friends** — add friends and manage requests
- **Groups** — create or join workout groups and share photos within them
- **Feed** — an Instagram-style feed of gym photos from friends, just for fun
- **Progress photos** — private photos on your profile to track changes over time
- **Profile** — your stats and photo grid

## Tech stack

- HTML5
- Tailwind CSS (Play CDN — no build step)
- Vanilla JavaScript (ES6 modules)
- `localStorage` for all data (no backend)

## Project structure

```
gym-app/
├── index.html              # SPA shell: header, nav, view mount point
├── css/
│   └── styles.css          # small custom layer over Tailwind
├── js/
│   ├── main.js             # entry point: boots the app, mounts the router
│   ├── store.js            # single source of truth for localStorage
│   ├── auth.js             # signup / login / logout / current user
│   ├── router.js           # hash-based view switching
│   └── views/
│       ├── auth.js         # login + signup screen
│       ├── feed.js         # gym photo feed
│       ├── friends.js      # add / list friends
│       ├── groups.js       # create / join groups + group detail
│       └── profile.js      # progress photos + stats
└── assets/                 # placeholder avatars / icons
```

## Running it

The app uses ES6 modules, which browsers refuse to load over `file://`. You need a local server:

1. Open the project in VS Code.
2. Install the **Live Server** extension.
3. Right-click `index.html` → **Open with Live Server**.

Any static server works (`npx serve`, `python -m http.server`, etc.) — opening the HTML file directly will not.

## Known limitations

- **Local only.** Data lives in one browser on one device. There are no real accounts and nothing is shared between users — "friends" and "groups" are simulated.
- **Photo storage is tiny.** `localStorage` caps around 5 MB and images are large, so only a handful of photos will fit. Fine for testing the flow, not for real use.
- Clearing browser data wipes everything.

## Roadmap

Swap the `localStorage` layer for a real backend (e.g. Supabase) to get genuine accounts, friends, groups, and photo storage that work across devices. Because all storage goes through `store.js`, this is the main file that would change.


